9/ Finally, if you’re wondering why housing and stock prices are going up, it’s because cheap money has no place to go. Cash savings will get eroded and bonds don’t pay enough. Real people may lose jobs and homes, but investors gain opportunities.

8/ Additionally, there is a question of velocity. At a time of uncertainty, people save more and spend less. More stimulus means more savings and not necessarily more spending. After vaccine is announced, velocity of money will increase drastically, forcing inflation up.

7/ The risk with the Fed’s approach is overshooting inflation targets. If inflation increases too fast, the stability of the USD as a unit of exchange is at risk. In theory, the Fed can pull back on stimulus by raising interest rates. In practice, this may not be done in time.

6/ Inflation is correlated to full employment. As more people become employed, and good candidates are harder to find, salaries begin to rise, and more money spent is on consumer goods, driving prices further up.

5/ There is an inverse relationship between inflation and interest rates. If rates are too high, you will keep cash in high interest savings or bonds. If rates are too low, you are likely to spend or invest your cash, borrow for a house, or take a loan for a business expansion.

4/ Inflation is viewed as a necessary side-effect to promote spending. If keeping your money in cash erodes it away, you are likely to invest it into a business, stocks, land or commodities. Investment creates jobs.

3/ The Fed has a dual mandate to achieve (1) stable prices and (2) maximum sustainable employment.

The Fed has two main tools to achieve this -  (1) quantitive easing or capital infusion,  and (2) lowering interest rates.

3/ U.S. suffers from chronic DEFLATION. This is because there is a constant shortage of dollars worldwide. Up to 80% of global business and debt is denominated in dollars. Global dependence on dollars is driving demand for alternative currencies - Digital Yuan and Digital Euro.

2/ Inflation between 2-3% is considered healthy. Inflation in the double digits, is called hyperinflation. 

We have seen this recently in Venezuela, Zimbabwe and Lebanon, where governments print too much money too fast, deeming that currency worthless.

1/ What is Inflation?

Inflation mean that prices of the same goods increase over time, making the purchasing power of each dollar LESS. 

That means the same car, house or loaf of bread now costs more.

Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago President Charles Evans said he would welcome 2.5% inflation in the U.S.

Why is inflation so important to the U.S.?

1995: Production in Russia decreases, while money supply increases. Inflation reaches 5000% per year.

5/ The #DeFi space is still incredibly risky and speculative. Be careful and do your own research. 

For the full article, read here: https://t.co/MK3eiT6qft

4.5/ Synthetic Asset Bridges - #Bitcoin is great as a store of value, but difficult to use as collateral. Creating a digital representation of Bitcoin allows it to be used in financial contracts. Bitcoin is currently being tokenized faster than it is being mined.

4.4/ Decentralized Prediction Markets, Options and Insurance - This next category is all about betting on something happening or not happening in the future, and includes decentralized prediction markets, on-chain options and insurance, in a fully automated matter.
4.3/ Asset Management Protocols - A recent category of #DeFi products creates frameworks for users to pool funds for investments akin to robo-advisors, automated funds, and asset aggregators.

4.2/ Decentralized Exchanges - Trading of securities and cryptocurrencies is typically done through platforms run by a third party. #DeFi exchanges eliminate middlemen and can act as a custodian of funds and digital assets in a peer-to-peer exchange.

4.1/ Borrowing and Lending  - #DeFi allows a user to programmatically take out a loan, without an application or even a bank account. The lender is the smart contract itself and interest rates are calculated algorithmically based on supply and demand.

1/ #DeFi stands for “Decentralized Finance”, which aims to recreate the traditional financial system with less, well, middlemen. Actions such as lending, borrowing, derivative products, buying and selling of securities, can now be done through a decentralized open-source network.
